To draw a chessboard in LaTeX based on a given FEN (Forsyth-Edwards Notation) notation, you can use the `skak` package. Here's an example of a LaTeX code that includes all the required commands and packages to draw a chessboard based on a FEN notation:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{skak}
\usepackage{xskak}

% Define the FEN notation as a command
\newcommand{\showFEN}[1]{
  \newgame
  \setboardfontsize{10pt}
  \hidemoves{
    \chessboard[
      setfen={#1},
      printbottom=false,
      showmover=false,
      pgfstyle=border,
      color=black,
      coloremphasis=white,
      boardfontsize=10pt,
    ]
  }
}

% Define the FEN notation for the example
\newcommand{\myFEN}{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

\begin{document}

% Show the chessboard based on the FEN notation
\showFEN{\myFEN}

\end{document}
```

This code creates a chessboard with the specified FEN notation in the command `\myFEN`. You can replace `\myFEN` with your own FEN notation.

The `skak` and `xskak` packages are used to handle chessboard and chess moves. The `\showFEN` command sets up the chessboard with the given FEN notation, and the `\chessboard` command draws the board. The `setfen` key-value is used to specify the FEN notation, and the `printbottom`, `showmover`, `pgfstyle`, `color`, `coloremphasis`, `boardfontsize` keys are used to customize the board appearance.

Note that you need to compile this code with `pdflatex` and the `--shell-escape` option, because the `xskak` package uses `gnuplot` to generate the chessboard.

