public class PowerOfThree {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 1) {
            return false;
        }
        return Math.log10(n) / Math.log10(3) % 1 == 0;
    }
}
```

The `isPowerOfThree` function takes an integer `n` as input, and returns a boolean value indicating whether `n` is a power of three.

The function first checks if `n` is negative. If it is, then it immediately returns `false`, since a negative number cannot be a power of three.

Next, the function calculates the logarithm of `n` in base 3, and checks if the result is an integer. This is done by taking the logarithm of `n` in base 10, and dividing it by the logarithm of 3 in base 10. The remainder of this division is then checked to see if it is equal to 0. If the remainder is 0, then the logarithm of `n` in base 3 is an integer, and `n` is a power of three.

Overall, this solution has a time complexity of O(1), since it performs a constant number of arithmetic operations. This is efficient enough to solve the problem in a real-world scenario.

